Z||000012||DolphinJoy||06-21-2001||05:34 PM||ecothedolphin@hotmail.com||Its amazing the number of cultures that have worshipped/revered/celebrated dolphins and whales.  I've listed a few below:<p>Greeks/Romans: Dolphins were seen as messangers of the Gods and were associated with Poseidon/Neptune, Aphrodite/Venus and Apollo<p>Sumerian: Dolphins were associated with the Sea god Ea-Oannes.<p>Egyptian:  Dolphins were connected to the goddess Isis.<p>Celtic:  Dolphins were attributed with well-worship and the powers of water.<p>Native American:  Dolphins (paticularly orcas) are seen as sent by the Gods.  They are sometimes regarded as tribal totems (ancestor spirits)<p>Australian Aboriginal:  Dolphins are also seen as totem animals by some tribes.<p>Arabia/Islam:  A whale supposedly supports the Earth.  According to some old Islamic mythology, Jonah's whale is one of the few animals allowed into Paradise.<p>Russia:  Again, a whale supports the Earth.<p>Slav:  Four whales were believed to support the Earth.<p>Christianity:  Dolphins, especially when entwined around a cross, represent the resurrection of Christ and man's salvation.  The whale was God's chosen animals to punish Jonah and is also symbolic of rebirth.<p>Inuit:  Whales and dolphins are said to have been created by the sea goddess Sedna.<p>Norse:  Whales were said to have magical powers and were the mounts of witches.<p>China:  A whale with the hands and feet of a man rules the ocean.  There are also legends of the Yangtse River Dolphin, the Baiji, which are very similar to Boto stories.<p>Buddhism:  Whales often appear on statues of the Buddha in Tibet.<p>Hinduism:  A huge fish, possibly a whale, is related to the god Vishnu.<p>Vietnam:  Whales and dolphins are greatly respected.  If one is killed or washed up on the beach, it is buried in a special temple and the locals mourn for it.<p>South America:  Some tribes used a Killer Whale motif on their ancient designs.<p>
